---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="About — Chi Tran">
  <Nav client:load />
  <main class="pt-[56px] md:pt-[60px]">
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="project-section flex flex-col min-h-[45vh] justify-center">
      <p class="section-label">— Hello</p>
      <h1
        class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-semibold italic text-primary leading-tight mt-2"
      >
        Hi there,<br />it's Chi!
      </h1>
      <p class="font-sans text-base md:text-lg text-subtitle italic mt-3">
        (Trần Tùng Chi, if we're being formal)
      </p>
      <p
        class="font-sans text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#3a302b] max-w-2xl mt-6"
      >
        A business student who believes the best strategy is a story well told —
        and that slowing down, whether in business or behind a camera, is almost
        always the right move.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- City trail divider -->
    <div class="px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-28 2xl:px-0 py-6 md:py-10 overflow-x-auto">
      <div
        class="flex items-center gap-3 font-sans text-sm md:text-base text-subtitle/50 whitespace-nowrap select-none"
      >
        <span class="text-primary/80 font-semibold">Hà Nội</span>
        <div class="w-8 md:w-14 h-px bg-primary/20 shrink-0"></div>
        <span>San Francisco</span>
        <div class="w-8 md:w-14 h-px bg-primary/20 shrink-0"></div>
        <span>Hà Nội</span>
        <div class="w-8 md:w-14 h-px bg-primary/20 shrink-0"></div>
        <span>Japan</span>
        <div class="w-8 md:w-14 h-px bg-primary/20 shrink-0"></div>
        <span class="text-primary/80 font-semibold">Houston</span>
        <span class="text-primary/40 ml-1 text-xs">✦ now</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- My Story -->
    <section class="project-section">
      <p class="section-label">— My Story</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">
        A Hà Nội girl learning to see the world, slowly.
      </h2>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>
          Growing up in Hà Nội taught me to notice the rhythm of everyday life.
          The city is busy and chaotic, but it's also full of small, quiet
          moments — people sitting on tiny plastic stools drinking tea, street
          vendors arranging fruit with more care than necessary, neighbours who
          have known each other for decades.
        </p>
        <p>
          Living there made me a watcher. I became interested in how people
          move, how they interact, how community builds itself in the spaces
          between words. That habit — looking a little closer before trying to
          understand — stayed with me. It shapes how I approach a business
          problem, how I build a brand, and how I decide when to press the
          shutter.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="project-section">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1">
        <div class="project-card">
          <span class="text-3xl mb-4 block leading-none">🏔</span>
          <h3 class="project-card-title">A small moment<br />in Hoà Bình</h3>
          <p class="project-card-body mt-3">
            On a trip to Hoà Bình, a mountainous province where several ethnic
            minority communities live, my team brought small electrical items as
            gifts: fans, lights. When we arrived, most couldn't be used. The
            outlets were different. Power cuts were frequent. It was a small
            moment, but it made something clear: solutions only work when
            designed with the local context in mind. That trip shaped how I
            think about business — not as abstract systems, but as decisions
            that directly affect people's lives. It stayed with me when I
            started BẢN.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Cross-cultural / adaptability -->
    <section class="project-section">
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>
          I've been moving since middle school: San Francisco from 7th through
          10th grade, then back to Việt Nam, a semester in Japan, now Houston.
          Each place required a different version of me. The hardest part was
          never the logistics. It was rebuilding small things from scratch:
          friendships, routines, confidence in how I communicate. I got faster
          at it over time. That kind of adaptability doesn't come from a
          classroom — it comes from having to figure it out, repeatedly, in
          places with different rules.
        </p>
        <p>
          Being between languages and cultures means I'm often looking for the
          version of an idea that works in both worlds. I think that makes me a
          more careful thinker, and a better communicator.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- I am... -->
    <section class="project-section">
      <p class="section-label">— I Am</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">A few things worth knowing.</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="project-card">
          <p
            class="font-display text-xl md:text-2xl italic font-semibold text-tertiary mb-3"
          >
            … probably at a café right now, on my second cup of matcha or egg
            coffee.
          </p>
          <p class="project-card-body">
            I love tea in all its forms: matcha, oolong, green, hojicha,
            whatever's good. But Vietnamese egg coffee (cà phê trứng) has my
            whole heart. It's creamy, rich, and requires absolutely no rush. I
            do my best thinking in slow, warm places.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card">
          <p
            class="font-display text-xl md:text-2xl italic font-semibold text-tertiary mb-3"
          >
            … still adjusting to a city where you need a car to get anywhere.
          </p>
          <p class="project-card-body">
            I grew up walking everywhere: Hà Nội's alleys, San Francisco's
            hills, Japan's impossibly good train system. Houston is many things,
            but walkable is not one of them. I miss being able to just step
            outside and go.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card">
          <p
            class="font-display text-xl md:text-2xl italic font-semibold text-tertiary mb-3"
          >
            … thinking in Vietnamese and writing in English, sometimes at the
            same time.
          </p>
          <p class="project-card-body">
            There are ideas that only have the right word in one language.
            Living between two has made me a more careful, more precise thinker
            — always looking for the version that works in both worlds.
            Sometimes the translation is the most interesting part.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What I bring -->
    <section class="project-section">
      <p class="section-label">— What I Bring to the Table</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">How I think about work.</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="project-card flex-row gap-6 items-start">
          <span class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-primary shrink-0"
            >01</span
          >
          <div>
            <h3 class="project-card-title">Strategy is storytelling</h3>
            <p class="project-card-body">
              The best business decisions aren't just efficient — they're
              meaningful. I approach strategy the same way I approach a
              photograph: looking for the frame that makes the whole picture
              make sense. Data tells you what happened. Story tells you why it
              matters.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card flex-row gap-6 items-start">
          <span class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-primary shrink-0"
            >02</span
          >
          <div>
            <h3 class="project-card-title">Observe before you act</h3>
            <p class="project-card-body">
              The Hoà Bình trip taught me this viscerally: showing up with the
              wrong solution, however well-intentioned, helps no one. I'd rather
              ask one more question than make one more assumption. The best
              insights come from looking closer, not faster.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card flex-row gap-6 items-start">
          <span class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-primary shrink-0"
            >03</span
          >
          <div>
            <h3 class="project-card-title">
              Cross-cultural fluency is a skill
            </h3>
            <p class="project-card-body">
              Not just linguistically, but in the deeper sense of understanding
              how context shapes meaning. What works in one culture may need
              translation in another. I've lived that across multiple countries,
              and I bring it to every team I'm part of.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Outside of work -->
    <section class="project-section">
      <p class="section-label">— Outside of Work</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">The rest of it.</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="project-card">
          <h3 class="project-card-title">
            🍵 A tea phase with no end in sight
          </h3>
          <p class="project-card-body mt-3">
            Matcha, oolong, jasmine, hojicha — I'm open to all of it. Vietnamese
            egg coffee holds a special place. Japan made me very serious about
            tea. I now own more tea than I have mugs for, which feels like a
            completely reasonable life choice.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card">
          <h3 class="project-card-title">
            📖 Reading outside of business school
          </h3>
          <p class="project-card-body mt-3">
            Essays, non-fiction, anything at the intersection of culture and
            ideas. I'm drawn to writers who notice things other people walk
            past. Current rotation: books about memory, craft, and how places
            shape people.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card">
          <h3 class="project-card-title">
            ✍︎ Writing something that may never be published
          </h3>
          <p class="project-card-body mt-3">
            Journaling, blog drafts, notes on things I'm still figuring out.
            Writing is how I understand what I actually think. If a post
            eventually makes it to the Playground, it went through at least
            three cups of tea and one deleted draft.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="project-card">
          <h3 class="project-card-title">
            🎞️ Waiting to find out what's on that last roll of film.
          </h3>
          <p class="project-card-body mt-3">
            I shoot on expired film, mostly Agfa Vista and Kodak Gold. The
            colors shift in ways you can't predict. You won't know what you got
            until weeks later. I find that deeply reassuring. Not everything
            needs to be immediate.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <section
      class="py-24 md:py-32 px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-24 flex flex-col items-center text-center"
    >
      <div class="w-12 h-px bg-primary mb-10"></div>
      <blockquote
        class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl italic font-semibold text-tertiary leading-snug max-w-3xl"
      >
        "The best thinking I've done has happened slowly, over something warm,
        in a place with no particular reason to hurry."
      </blockquote>
      <div class="w-12 h-px bg-primary mt-10"></div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
